\section{Excitation Scheme}\index{FDTD!excitation}
The excitation source plays a very important role in the FDTD simulation \cite{Mittra_CFDTD_04} and is set up here by assigning a Gaussian time function to specific electric field components in the FDTD space lattice.

\subsection{Gaussian pulse}\index{Gaussian pulse}
%In common with the absorbing boundary for the mesh truncation and the conformal technique for handling arbitrary object, the excitation source play a very important role in the $FDTD$ simulation \cite{Mittra_CFDTD_04}; however, the choice of the source has not received as much attention in the literature as have the others, and, hence, we discuss them here briefly.
\subsubsection{Analog Mathematical Basis}
The Gaussian function is formally given by
\be\label{gaussian_pulse_1}
G\left(t\right)=A_0e^{\left[-\left(t-t_0\right)^2/2t_w^2\right]}
\ee
where $t_w$ is the standard deviation and relates the line-width at half-height by the relationship
\be\label{gaussian_pulse_2}
t_{1/2}=\sqrt{8\ln\left(2\right)}t_w=\left(2.235482\right)t_w
\ee
The Gaussian function maximizes to $A_0$ at $t=t_0$ and is zero at $t=\pm\infty$. Plots of this function for time \& frequency domains are shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig:gaussian_pulse_21}.


\subsubsection{Discrete Mathematical Basis}\label{Discrete_Math_GPulse}
In FDTD representation the Gaussian function, must be done using discrete mathematics. The waveform will be represented by a specified number of points, and the previous analog function can be adjusted to evaluate at each point according to
\be\label{gaussian_pulse_5}
G(t)=A_0e^{\left[-\left(n-n_0\right)^2/2n_\omega^2\right]}
\ee
where, $t=n\bigtriangleup t$, $t_0=n_0\bigtriangleup t$ \& $t_\omega=n_\omega\bigtriangleup t$

