\subsection{Source}\index{FDTD!source}
Source in FDTD excitation may be either hard source or soft source.
\subsubsection{Hard source}\index{FDTD!source!hard}
Hard source is set up by forcing a desired time function to the electric field components. For example, for Gaussian input pulse, the $E_x$ components at time step $n$ ($t=n\bigtriangleup t$) are given by \cite{Prabir_thesis}:
\be\label{fdtd_hard_sourc_gaussian_excitation}
E^n_{x_i,j,k}=G(t)
\ee
The input waveform generated by hard source excitation is exactly the desired waveform with amplitude $A_0$. But, the hard source simulates a reflecting barrier at the source plane and thus causes spurious reflection.


\subsubsection{Soft source}\index{FDTD!source!soft}
In this scheme, the field value, obtained from the time function, is added to the FDTD update field value at the source plane at each time step. For Gaussian input pulse, the $E_x$ components at time step $n$ are given by \cite{Prabir_thesis}:
\be\label{fdtd_soft_sourc_gaussian excitation}
E^n_{x_i,j,k}=E^n_{x_i,j,k}+G(t)
\ee
There will not be any spurious reflection from the source plane for soft source. The disadvantage of soft source is that the waveform will not be the exact one. The input waveform will not be of amplitude $A_0$ and the wave shape may not be the exact one. %As there will not be any spurious reflection from source plane for soft source, this excitation scheme has been utilized in this work.














